1
00:00:06,881 --> 00:00:08,001
BOY: Judy!

2
00:00:08,121 --> 00:00:11,321
-Judy, what are you doing? Come on!
-JUDY: I want to hear the music.

3
00:00:14,081 --> 00:00:15,121
You're going to get me in trouble.

4
00:00:16,161 --> 00:00:18,201
Everyone knows
there are ghosts in the hill.

5
00:00:18,281 --> 00:00:20,081
Wait! You'll hear it in a minute.

6
00:00:22,561 --> 00:00:23,641
That's ghosts.

7
00:00:23,721 --> 00:00:25,441
If you stay out here,
listening to ghosts,

8
00:00:25,521 --> 00:00:27,681
they will come out
of the hill and eat you.

9
00:00:27,761 --> 00:00:29,841
-They won't.
-They will.

10
00:00:30,041 --> 00:00:32,241
And I'll get the blame. Now, come on.

11
00:00:39,161 --> 00:00:41,241
(MUSIC PLAYING)

12
00:00:42,561 --> 00:00:44,001
I can hear it.

13
00:00:46,001 --> 00:00:47,121
Judy, no!

14
00:00:48,121 --> 00:00:49,121
(VOICE WHISPERING)

15
00:00:50,241 --> 00:00:51,281
Judy!

16
00:00:52,441 --> 00:00:53,441
(VOICE WHISPERING)

17
00:00:54,081 --> 00:00:56,041
CROW: (CAWING) Doc-tor.

18
00:00:56,841 --> 00:01:02,121
Doctor. Doctor. Doctor. Doctor.

19
00:01:02,681 --> 00:01:04,681
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

20
00:01:45,241 --> 00:01:47,281
NARDOLE: (SIGHS) Where are we now?

21
00:01:47,361 --> 00:01:50,641
BILL: Aberdeen. Scotland.
Second century AD.

22
00:01:50,721 --> 00:01:53,281
THE DOCTOR: You weren't complaining
when it was Mars, were you?

23
00:01:53,361 --> 00:01:56,561
So why is Scotland suddenly
more important than guarding the vault

24
00:01:56,641 --> 00:01:58,241
and keeping your sacred oath?

25
00:01:58,361 --> 00:02:00,801
She thinks she knows
more about Romans than me.

26
00:02:01,041 --> 00:02:02,521
Oh, that's explained everything,
thank you.

27
00:02:02,601 --> 00:02:05,361
You don't know more about
the Ninth Legion than me. You don't!

28
00:02:05,601 --> 00:02:08,841
I read the book. I loved the book.
I read everything...

29
00:02:08,921 --> 00:02:10,201
They disappeared.

30
00:02:10,681 --> 00:02:11,761
Except they didn't.

31
00:02:11,841 --> 00:02:13,841
THE DOCTOR:
They were annihilated in battle.

32
00:02:13,921 --> 00:02:15,761
Then where's the big pile of bodies?

33
00:02:16,041 --> 00:02:18,601
-Oh, I don't know.
-So where's the Ninth Legion?

34
00:02:18,681 --> 00:02:20,881
If they'd left,
they should still be leaving.

35
00:02:20,961 --> 00:02:24,441
Can you see 5,000 Roman soldiers
marching south?

36
00:02:25,361 --> 00:02:26,361
-Mmm.
-BILL: Down there.

37
00:02:26,761 --> 00:02:27,921
By the river.

38
00:02:28,001 --> 00:02:29,921
They'd have followed the river.
That's what they did.

39
00:02:30,361 --> 00:02:33,241
So much that you don't understand
about Roman Britain...

40
00:02:33,761 --> 00:02:35,321
I got an A star.

41
00:02:35,521 --> 00:02:38,001
-Ooh, got an A star!
-I've lived in Roman Britain.

42
00:02:38,081 --> 00:02:41,401
Governed. Farmed. Juggled.

43
00:02:41,481 --> 00:02:43,801
Speaking as a former vestal virgin,
second class, I can assure you...

44
00:02:43,881 --> 00:02:47,681
I bet you there is a Roman legion
down there.

45
00:02:47,761 --> 00:02:49,881
Hang on! What, what, second class?

46
00:02:50,161 --> 00:02:54,201
Fine, you go and check the river,
I'll go and find their last battlefield.

47
00:02:54,281 --> 00:02:58,721
Fine. I'll meet you back here
with a Roman soldier.

48
00:02:59,041 --> 00:03:00,961
Yeah, but seriously, second class?

49
00:03:01,281 --> 00:03:03,041
Yeah, it's a long story. Come on.

50
00:03:24,881 --> 00:03:26,401
WOMAN: We honour you, Mother.

51
00:03:30,001 --> 00:03:31,321
(SOBS) We honour you.

52
00:03:33,441 --> 00:03:34,801
We honour all our dead.

53
00:03:36,841 --> 00:03:38,241
I honour you, Father.

54
00:03:39,361 --> 00:03:40,761
We honour all our dead.

55
00:03:42,521 --> 00:03:43,881
I honour you, Mother.

56
00:03:44,441 --> 00:03:46,681
I honour you, Mother. (KISSES)

57
00:03:47,121 --> 00:03:48,961
I honour all our dead.

58
00:03:49,041 --> 00:03:50,041
(TWIG CRACKS)

59
00:03:52,201 --> 00:03:53,241
(SCREAMS)

60
00:04:14,041 --> 00:04:15,121
(GASPS)

61
00:04:15,441 --> 00:04:16,441
(GRUNTS)

62
00:04:17,921 --> 00:04:18,921
Oh!

63
00:04:24,681 --> 00:04:26,561
THE DOCTOR: 5,000 Roman soldiers.

64
00:04:26,841 --> 00:04:30,361
Eyes peeled. They must have left
some kind of mark on the landscape.

65
00:04:30,441 --> 00:04:33,801
Burning huts, slaughtered locals,
sweetie wrappers...

66
00:04:34,921 --> 00:04:35,921
CROW: (CAWING) Dark!

67
00:04:37,481 --> 00:04:39,521
Dark! Dark!

68
00:04:40,081 --> 00:04:41,081
Doctor!

69
00:04:42,201 --> 00:04:43,961
-CROW: (CAWING) Doc. Doc-tor.
-Look!

70
00:04:44,521 --> 00:04:47,361
A stone cairn. Pictish civilisation.

71
00:04:48,081 --> 00:04:49,081
NARDOLE: The bird!

72
00:04:49,321 --> 00:04:52,161
-What about it?
-He said, "Dark."

73
00:04:53,241 --> 00:04:54,641
Yes, well, that's why we're hurrying,

74
00:04:54,721 --> 00:04:56,481
because there's not much light
at this time of day.

75
00:04:56,561 --> 00:04:57,841
But it talked.

76
00:04:57,921 --> 00:05:00,401
Well, of course it did.
It's a crow. All crows talk.

77
00:05:00,681 --> 00:05:02,881
-Well, they don't talk in the future.
-Course they do.

78
00:05:02,961 --> 00:05:05,401
Human beings just stopped having
intelligent conversations with them.

79
00:05:05,721 --> 00:05:09,441
-And they all took a bit of a huff.
-Crows in the future are all in a huff?

80
00:05:09,801 --> 00:05:11,921
Course they are. Haven't you noticed
that noise they make?

81
00:05:12,001 --> 00:05:14,121
It's like a mass sulk. Come on!

82
00:05:14,201 --> 00:05:16,041
The sooner we get there,
the sooner we'll know the answer.

83
00:05:16,361 --> 00:05:17,681
-NARDOLE: Yeah. I know, but...
-(CROWS CAWING)

84
00:05:17,761 --> 00:05:21,641
THE DOCTOR:
Picts, early Celts, loved stone cairns.

85
00:05:22,321 --> 00:05:24,961
They built them under the ground,
but close to the sky.

86
00:05:26,481 --> 00:05:29,441
They think they're doors between worlds.

87
00:05:30,281 --> 00:05:32,001
Iron Age churches.

88
00:05:33,601 --> 00:05:38,161
-What do you always find near churches?
-Women in hats.

89
00:05:38,361 --> 00:05:41,121
Exactly! Human settlement.

90
00:05:42,241 --> 00:05:44,281
It's a little bit damp, though,
isn't it?

91
00:05:46,841 --> 00:05:49,161
It's Scotland. It's supposed to be damp.

92
00:05:52,121 --> 00:05:54,481
BILL: Oh! A Roman soldier!

93
00:05:55,161 --> 00:05:57,841
Ah, I wish I'd studied Latin
so you could understand me.

94
00:05:58,601 --> 00:05:59,681
I understand you.

95
00:06:00,161 --> 00:06:01,161
Sorry, what?

96
00:06:01,641 --> 00:06:02,761
I understand you.

97
00:06:03,521 --> 00:06:06,641
But, you're...
But you're speaking English.

98
00:06:07,001 --> 00:06:08,001
What's English?

99
00:06:08,121 --> 00:06:09,681
What you're speaking in.

100
00:06:09,761 --> 00:06:10,761
You're speaking Latin.

101
00:06:11,201 --> 00:06:12,361
(LAUGHS) I'm not.

102
00:06:12,441 --> 00:06:14,921
That's Latin.
You just said that in Latin.

103
00:06:17,081 --> 00:06:18,921
Ha! It's The Doctor.

104
00:06:19,561 --> 00:06:21,281
Or the TARDIS. Or both.

105
00:06:21,361 --> 00:06:25,801
Something telepathic.
Link. Auto-translate.

106
00:06:26,161 --> 00:06:28,081
That's why everyone in this place
speaks English.

107
00:06:28,161 --> 00:06:29,721
What on Earth are you talking about?

108
00:06:30,201 --> 00:06:31,921
Oh, my God. It even does lip-sync.

109
00:06:32,401 --> 00:06:33,401
Who are you?

110
00:06:33,481 --> 00:06:34,641
I'm Bill.

111
00:06:37,641 --> 00:06:39,241
Are you from the Ninth Legion?

112
00:06:40,801 --> 00:06:41,801
Yes.

113
00:06:42,081 --> 00:06:45,001
Yes! Where have you been?

114
00:06:45,441 --> 00:06:46,441
Don't you know?

115
00:06:47,521 --> 00:06:48,521
Know what?

116
00:06:50,361 --> 00:06:52,041
Did you see what happened to us?

117
00:06:57,561 --> 00:06:59,441
It's as if his bones have disintegrated.

118
00:06:59,521 --> 00:07:00,601
Oh!

119
00:07:01,361 --> 00:07:02,561
What could do that?

120
00:07:03,241 --> 00:07:05,761
Complete and total absence
of any kind of sunlight.

121
00:07:06,081 --> 00:07:08,801
Huh. Death by Scotland. (CHUCKLES)

122
00:07:10,881 --> 00:07:11,881
-No.
-No.

123
00:07:12,161 --> 00:07:13,761
It should take decades.

124
00:07:13,841 --> 00:07:15,641
This happened a short while ago.

125
00:07:17,761 --> 00:07:18,761
This is alien.

126
00:07:18,881 --> 00:07:19,921
Right.

127
00:07:20,681 --> 00:07:21,681
Good-o!

128
00:07:21,881 --> 00:07:24,401
Question is, where are the rest of them?

129
00:07:26,161 --> 00:07:28,521
(GROANS) Just wanna go back to bed.

130
00:07:34,041 --> 00:07:35,561
THE DOCTOR: There they are.

131
00:07:36,401 --> 00:07:37,841
The Ninth Legion.

132
00:07:40,521 --> 00:07:42,161
They're a big pile of bodies.

133
00:07:44,041 --> 00:07:45,681
Not always fun to be right.

134
00:07:46,201 --> 00:07:47,521
This wasn't long ago.

135
00:07:47,601 --> 00:07:50,241
Whatever did this, is close by.
We need to find Bill.

136
00:07:50,681 --> 00:07:52,321
Don't move! Stay where you are!

137
00:07:52,401 --> 00:07:53,401
(GASPS)

138
00:07:57,001 --> 00:07:58,641
(SNARLING)

139
00:08:06,081 --> 00:08:07,081
(GRUNTS)

140
00:08:10,681 --> 00:08:13,921
SOLDIER: The barbarians
dug these traps everywhere.

141
00:08:15,801 --> 00:08:16,921
(GRUNTS)

142
00:08:22,321 --> 00:08:23,761
-(SNARLS)
-BILL: What was that?

143
00:08:23,841 --> 00:08:26,001
SOLDIER: It's what slaughtered
the Ninth.

144
00:08:30,041 --> 00:08:31,161
Can you see it?

145
00:08:32,481 --> 00:08:35,441
Attacked us with a thing. A monster.

146
00:08:43,961 --> 00:08:45,201
There's nothing here.

147
00:08:47,441 --> 00:08:49,321
I've got to get back to the others.

148
00:08:49,921 --> 00:08:51,201
You said they were wiped out.

149
00:08:51,281 --> 00:08:52,961
There were survivors. A handful.

150
00:08:53,681 --> 00:08:54,721
I can't leave them.

151
00:08:54,801 --> 00:08:55,801
Of course not.

152
00:08:56,401 --> 00:08:59,161
We found a hiding place.
We might still be safe there.

153
00:09:03,561 --> 00:09:05,001
BILL: So what was it like, this monster?

154
00:09:05,081 --> 00:09:06,121
SOLDIER: I don't know.

155
00:09:06,201 --> 00:09:09,721
But we deserted.
We were the ones who couldn't face it.

156
00:09:10,921 --> 00:09:13,121
Roman soldiers don't run.

157
00:09:13,881 --> 00:09:14,881
And we did.

158
00:09:15,641 --> 00:09:16,641
What?

159
00:09:16,761 --> 00:09:17,841
(BRANCHES CRACKING)

160
00:09:17,921 --> 00:09:19,361
(ROARING)

161
00:09:22,481 --> 00:09:23,561
SOLDIER: They're underground.

162
00:09:23,641 --> 00:09:25,001
By the river,
there's a carving of a fish.

163
00:09:25,361 --> 00:09:27,361
Was that it? The monster?

164
00:09:27,641 --> 00:09:28,641
(SCREECHING)

165
00:09:29,881 --> 00:09:30,921
(SCREAMING)

166
00:09:31,921 --> 00:09:32,921
No!

167
00:09:35,161 --> 00:09:36,161
(PANTING)

168
00:09:36,681 --> 00:09:37,681
(ROARING)

169
00:09:59,041 --> 00:10:00,801
(LOUD ROARING)

170
00:10:04,601 --> 00:10:05,681
Ah!

171
00:10:08,441 --> 00:10:10,121
Block the entrance! Quickly!

172
00:10:10,641 --> 00:10:11,721
Hurry up!

173
00:10:19,001 --> 00:10:20,001
(GRUNTS)

174
00:10:22,481 --> 00:10:24,321
MAN 1: How long will that hold?
MAN 2: Not for long.

175
00:10:24,401 --> 00:10:25,401
Ah!

176
00:10:25,481 --> 00:10:27,041
Now bring her through.

177
00:10:27,441 --> 00:10:29,401
Where we can have a better look at her.

178
00:10:41,881 --> 00:10:44,721
SOLDIER: You do realise the beast
now knows where we are.

179
00:10:48,521 --> 00:10:50,481
-You're not one of the barbarians?
-No.

180
00:10:51,961 --> 00:10:52,961
So...

181
00:10:53,241 --> 00:10:55,761
-You are the Ninth Legion!
-We are what's left.

182
00:10:56,281 --> 00:10:57,281
Simon should be back.

183
00:10:57,361 --> 00:10:59,961
SOLDIER 1: He was looking for the road.
Our route south, did you see him?

184
00:11:00,601 --> 00:11:03,001
-Yeah.
-Well, where is he?

185
00:11:08,841 --> 00:11:10,681
I'm sorry, the creature killed him.

186
00:11:12,761 --> 00:11:14,521
What is it, that thing?
Where did it come from?

187
00:11:14,601 --> 00:11:15,601
Killed him?

188
00:11:15,681 --> 00:11:19,801
Yeah, he was covered
in this like, black slime.

189
00:11:20,961 --> 00:11:22,481
SOLDIER 2: It knows where we are.

190
00:11:22,561 --> 00:11:23,841
We'll all die here in the dark.

191
00:11:23,921 --> 00:11:25,361
No one is going to die.

192
00:11:32,201 --> 00:11:35,561
THE DOCTOR: Oh, for heaven's sake,
how long are you going to keep us here?

193
00:11:35,641 --> 00:11:37,561
Couldn't we have seats?

194
00:11:37,641 --> 00:11:39,241
What about the Wi-Fi code,
how about that?

195
00:11:39,321 --> 00:11:41,601
MAN: Don't move! Don't speak.

196
00:11:41,681 --> 00:11:42,961
Kar will be here soon.

197
00:11:43,241 --> 00:11:45,441
-Who's Kar?
-The keeper of the gate.

198
00:11:45,801 --> 00:11:46,801
My sister.

199
00:11:47,201 --> 00:11:48,961
Well, let's hope
she's the brains of the family.

200
00:11:49,441 --> 00:11:52,241
Because there's a big bad wolf
of a monster out there,

201
00:11:52,321 --> 00:11:53,681
and you live in a house of sticks.

202
00:11:53,761 --> 00:11:55,961
Nice, here, isn't it? Yeah, yeah,

203
00:11:56,041 --> 00:11:58,121
I like what you've done
with the place, yeah.

204
00:11:59,161 --> 00:12:02,601
Yeah, would you like some popcorn?

205
00:12:02,681 --> 00:12:04,961
Won't take me a jiffy to make.

206
00:12:05,361 --> 00:12:06,921
What are you doing?

207
00:12:07,001 --> 00:12:09,841
-I'm ingratiating myself.
-Stop it, it's nauseating.

208
00:12:09,921 --> 00:12:11,001
It's called charm.

209
00:12:11,081 --> 00:12:12,641
I'm against it.

210
00:12:12,721 --> 00:12:14,761
-I'm against charm.
-Yeah, we all know that.

211
00:12:14,841 --> 00:12:17,201
I said don't move!

212
00:12:17,281 --> 00:12:18,281
-I'm rooted.
-Shh!

213
00:12:20,401 --> 00:12:21,761
Does anybody hear that?

214
00:12:22,881 --> 00:12:24,401
Do you know what that sound was?

215
00:12:24,601 --> 00:12:25,601
What?

216
00:12:27,161 --> 00:12:31,441
That was the sound of my patience
shattering into a billion little pieces.

217
00:12:31,521 --> 00:12:33,761
Now, there are only two things
that I need to know.

218
00:12:33,841 --> 00:12:37,241
Where is my friend
and what destroyed the Roman army?

219
00:12:37,321 --> 00:12:40,121
-(DOOR OPENS)
-I destroyed the Roman army.

220
00:12:41,881 --> 00:12:46,561
Really? What, you? Just on your own?
That's quite a trick.

221
00:12:46,641 --> 00:12:47,921
I'm the gatekeeper.

222
00:12:48,001 --> 00:12:49,121
Gatekeeper? What gate?

223
00:12:49,201 --> 00:12:51,361
Didn't you hear the call?
Where were you?

224
00:12:51,441 --> 00:12:53,121
I had to find the gatekeeper's things.

225
00:12:53,201 --> 00:12:55,121
Sorry, wait a minute,
are you the mighty warrior

226
00:12:55,201 --> 00:12:56,401
that we've all been waiting for?

227
00:12:56,481 --> 00:12:58,041
Where are all the grown-ups?

228
00:12:59,561 --> 00:13:00,681
There was a great battle.

229
00:13:00,881 --> 00:13:03,201
A great battle and we beat the Romans!

230
00:13:03,281 --> 00:13:05,441
Kar beat them, that's all that matters.

231
00:13:05,521 --> 00:13:07,801
Yes, but she's not a warrior,
she's an embryo.

232
00:13:07,881 --> 00:13:09,321
What did you do?
Throw your action figures at them?

233
00:13:09,401 --> 00:13:10,521
Listen, Roman.

234
00:13:10,601 --> 00:13:13,041
We're not Roman.
We're not part of the Roman army.

235
00:13:13,121 --> 00:13:16,721
No, we're not even slightly Italian.
I mean, I do a mean Spag Bol...

236
00:13:16,801 --> 00:13:18,641
Let me tell you about the Romans!

237
00:13:19,841 --> 00:13:22,201
They are the robbers of this world.

238
00:13:22,281 --> 00:13:26,321
When they've thieved everything on land,
they'll rob the sea.

239
00:13:27,001 --> 00:13:30,281
If their enemies are rich,
they'll take all they have.

240
00:13:31,521 --> 00:13:34,961
If their enemies are poor,
they'll make slaves of them.

241
00:13:35,841 --> 00:13:38,481
Their work is robbery,

242
00:13:38,561 --> 00:13:40,921
slaughter, plunder.

243
00:13:42,121 --> 00:13:44,681
They do this work
and they call it empire.

244
00:13:46,041 --> 00:13:47,961
They make deserts
and they call it peace.

245
00:13:48,641 --> 00:13:50,641
Yeah, but you gotta love
the indoor toilets, yeah?

246
00:13:50,721 --> 00:13:52,561
They're not conquerors, they're cowards.

247
00:13:52,641 --> 00:13:54,081
They're also all dead.

248
00:13:54,681 --> 00:13:56,921
There's an awful lot
of dead cowards out there.

249
00:13:58,041 --> 00:14:00,081
And I don't believe
that you killed them.

250
00:14:00,321 --> 00:14:01,321
Because the thing is,

251
00:14:01,401 --> 00:14:03,281
you said gate,
you called yourself gatekeeper,

252
00:14:03,361 --> 00:14:04,441
and you mentioned gate weapons,

253
00:14:04,521 --> 00:14:06,401
so I've got to wonder
what kind of a gate is that

254
00:14:06,481 --> 00:14:07,841
and what's on the other side.

255
00:14:07,921 --> 00:14:09,561
-And yes, you're absolutely right.
-Right?

256
00:14:09,641 --> 00:14:11,481
I am extremely quick.

257
00:14:11,561 --> 00:14:14,321
Listen, you are all very, very angry.

258
00:14:14,401 --> 00:14:16,481
But really, you're just very scared.

259
00:14:16,921 --> 00:14:20,201
But for now, would you mind awfully
all just jumping out of your skins,

260
00:14:20,281 --> 00:14:22,521
and allowing Nardole and I
to escape in the confusion?

261
00:14:22,601 --> 00:14:23,601
Who are you?

262
00:14:23,681 --> 00:14:24,681
Let me explain.

263
00:14:24,761 --> 00:14:25,921
-(EXPLODING)
-(SCREAMING)

264
00:14:31,641 --> 00:14:34,601
(LOUD ROARING)

265
00:14:37,521 --> 00:14:39,001
CROW: (CAWING) Monster!

266
00:14:41,961 --> 00:14:43,401
NARDOLE: We're looking for Bill, right?

267
00:14:43,481 --> 00:14:45,641
No, we're looking for the maximum danger
in the immediate area,

268
00:14:45,721 --> 00:14:47,441
and walking right into it.

269
00:14:47,801 --> 00:14:49,081
Yeah, but what about Bill?

270
00:14:49,161 --> 00:14:53,961
Well, if she's there, we're saving her.
If she's not, she's safe already.

271
00:14:54,041 --> 00:14:56,561
Trust me, this is not my first rodeo.

272
00:14:57,521 --> 00:15:00,161
Now, they think these cairns
are gateways between worlds.

273
00:15:02,241 --> 00:15:04,761
Given that they
keep going on about gates.

274
00:15:06,641 --> 00:15:08,281
And possibly, they're right.

275
00:15:13,521 --> 00:15:14,601
(GASPS)

276
00:15:16,441 --> 00:15:17,561
No...

277
00:15:18,521 --> 00:15:19,721
WOMAN: The gate's opening.

278
00:15:19,801 --> 00:15:22,241
-Your friend won't be coming back.
- (EXCLAIMS)

279
00:15:22,521 --> 00:15:23,841
(RUMBLING)

280
00:16:06,161 --> 00:16:07,361
(SNARLS)

281
00:16:07,441 --> 00:16:11,801
NARDOLE: However, the human ship
was called the Mary Celeste.

282
00:16:11,881 --> 00:16:13,401
Something like that. Anyway.

283
00:16:13,481 --> 00:16:17,241
The Enzomadons assumed
that any species they encountered

284
00:16:17,321 --> 00:16:20,561
would communicate as they did,
by digesting each other.

285
00:16:20,641 --> 00:16:24,721
The Enzomadon ambassador got through
the whole crew,

286
00:16:24,801 --> 00:16:27,641
and then very sadly
choked on a lifeboat.

287
00:16:28,161 --> 00:16:29,441
So... You're back!

288
00:16:30,241 --> 00:16:32,041
They said you would
probably never come back.

289
00:16:32,321 --> 00:16:33,721
I was in there for seconds.

290
00:16:34,241 --> 00:16:35,241
Two days.

291
00:16:46,641 --> 00:16:48,321
It's an inter dimensional temporal rift.

292
00:16:49,601 --> 00:16:53,601
A second in there
equates to days of time on this side.

293
00:16:54,001 --> 00:16:55,441
I was in there for two days?

294
00:16:55,521 --> 00:16:57,561
And eight hours, five minutes and...

295
00:16:57,641 --> 00:16:58,801
That's good then, isn't it?

296
00:16:58,881 --> 00:17:01,761
-Good?
-Plenty of time for you to find Bill.

297
00:17:02,241 --> 00:17:03,241
Oh.

298
00:17:03,561 --> 00:17:05,841
I looked. They helped me look.

299
00:17:05,921 --> 00:17:07,321
How hard did you look?

300
00:17:08,041 --> 00:17:09,041
I think we've lost her, Doctor.

301
00:17:09,201 --> 00:17:12,441
No, no, no, no.
We just don't know where she is.

302
00:17:12,521 --> 00:17:14,001
Not the same thing at all. Come on.

303
00:17:15,521 --> 00:17:17,921
NARDOLE: I'll tell you
about the Lusitania later.

304
00:17:18,001 --> 00:17:19,561
Oh, keep an eye out for Bill.

305
00:17:20,801 --> 00:17:22,361
SOLDIER: You have to move again.

306
00:17:22,441 --> 00:17:24,681
Stay in the sunlight.
It burns off the slime.

307
00:17:26,281 --> 00:17:27,281
Here.

308
00:17:29,081 --> 00:17:31,161
-Thanks.
-No problem.

309
00:17:33,121 --> 00:17:34,121
Are you hungry?

310
00:17:35,401 --> 00:17:36,401
Come on, you have to eat.

311
00:17:36,481 --> 00:17:38,081
-How much food have we got left?
-Enough.

312
00:17:38,161 --> 00:17:39,201
Really?

313
00:17:39,281 --> 00:17:40,721
Shut up, Cornelius.

314
00:17:41,281 --> 00:17:42,281
Go on, eat it.

315
00:17:43,801 --> 00:17:45,801
It's two days, you haven't had anything.

316
00:17:46,201 --> 00:17:47,721
I've never been lost this long.

317
00:17:47,801 --> 00:17:49,201
-I need to find him.
-Who?

318
00:17:49,281 --> 00:17:50,881
The Doctor. My friend.

319
00:17:51,441 --> 00:17:53,761
I don't know what I'm going to do
if I can't find him.

320
00:17:54,121 --> 00:17:56,281
Well, we will look after you.

321
00:17:58,081 --> 00:17:59,961
I have to find my way home somehow.

322
00:18:01,321 --> 00:18:03,361
This is the safest place to be.

323
00:18:04,601 --> 00:18:06,161
The beast is still out there.

324
00:18:13,161 --> 00:18:14,201
You came back.

325
00:18:14,481 --> 00:18:17,281
-Did you know what was in there?
-The gate?

326
00:18:17,681 --> 00:18:20,841
A portal between dimensions.
Do you know what's on the other side?

327
00:18:24,041 --> 00:18:25,841
Oh, you don't know anything, do you?

328
00:18:25,961 --> 00:18:29,761
You just stand around making speeches
and waving a TV aerial about.

329
00:18:31,481 --> 00:18:32,641
Shall I tell you what's in there?

330
00:18:33,041 --> 00:18:36,481
No. It's called the eater of light
and we held it back.

331
00:18:36,881 --> 00:18:39,161
Every generation,
a new warrior went into the gate

332
00:18:39,241 --> 00:18:41,521
and fought the eater of light
so it couldn't break through.

333
00:18:41,601 --> 00:18:43,161
But the creature did break through.

334
00:18:44,401 --> 00:18:47,481
It broke through
and it destroyed the whole Ninth Legion.

335
00:18:47,921 --> 00:18:50,441
It's weak, it's nearly dead,
it will die soon.

336
00:18:50,521 --> 00:18:51,561
Well, let's hope so.

337
00:18:51,801 --> 00:18:54,721
Because there are millions more,
just like it, on the other side.

338
00:18:54,801 --> 00:18:56,481
And very soon, all of them
will find their way

339
00:18:56,561 --> 00:18:57,961
through to this dimension.

340
00:18:59,201 --> 00:19:00,441
Then I'll hold them back.

341
00:19:00,521 --> 00:19:01,521
You'll hold them back?

342
00:19:01,601 --> 00:19:05,161
What, with your lollipop
and your kitty face paint?

343
00:19:05,241 --> 00:19:07,441
And your crazy,
novelty monster killing tool?

344
00:19:07,521 --> 00:19:09,121
Are you holding that thing
the right way up by the way?

345
00:19:09,201 --> 00:19:10,401
I don't want your help!

346
00:19:10,481 --> 00:19:11,761
But I'm all you've got.

347
00:19:11,841 --> 00:19:13,361
Believe me, I'm on your side.

348
00:19:13,881 --> 00:19:14,881
(SCREAMING)

349
00:19:14,961 --> 00:19:16,241
Come on, let's go!

350
00:19:18,201 --> 00:19:19,561
SOLDIER: We're all in this together.

351
00:19:20,121 --> 00:19:21,481
You're going to be fine.

352
00:19:21,921 --> 00:19:25,081
Marcus was hurt, like you,
and the sunlight healed him in the end.

353
00:19:25,521 --> 00:19:26,921
-I am feeling better.
-Good.

354
00:19:27,241 --> 00:19:29,801
Yeah, don't worry, Bill.
Lucius will look after you.

355
00:19:30,001 --> 00:19:31,521
Shut up, Cornelius!

356
00:19:34,081 --> 00:19:35,321
Uh...

357
00:19:35,761 --> 00:19:36,761
Lucius...

358
00:19:37,281 --> 00:19:41,441
Right, listen, there's
something I should explain.

359
00:19:41,521 --> 00:19:42,561
What?

360
00:19:42,641 --> 00:19:45,801
This is probably
just a really difficult idea.

361
00:19:46,801 --> 00:19:49,921
I don't like men. That way.

362
00:19:51,241 --> 00:19:52,241
What, not ever?

363
00:19:52,681 --> 00:19:54,681
Nah, not ever.

364
00:19:56,761 --> 00:19:58,161
-Only women.
-Oh.

365
00:19:58,481 --> 00:20:01,521
All right, yeah, I got it.
You're like Vitus, then?

366
00:20:02,321 --> 00:20:04,041
-What?
-He only likes men.

367
00:20:04,121 --> 00:20:05,121
Some men.

368
00:20:06,081 --> 00:20:08,161
Better looking men than you, Lucius.

369
00:20:08,361 --> 00:20:10,441
-(LAUGHS)
-I don't think it's narrow-minded.

370
00:20:10,521 --> 00:20:12,641
I think it's fine.
You know what you like.

371
00:20:13,081 --> 00:20:14,441
And you like both?

372
00:20:14,521 --> 00:20:17,801
I'm just ordinary.
You know, like men and women.

373
00:20:18,241 --> 00:20:22,041
(LAUGHS) Well,
isn't this all very modern?

374
00:20:22,121 --> 00:20:23,721
Hey, not everyone has to be modern.

375
00:20:24,201 --> 00:20:27,441
I think it's really sweet
that you're so restricted.

376
00:20:28,961 --> 00:20:30,681
-Cheers.
-We can be friends, though.

377
00:20:30,761 --> 00:20:32,961
You know, I did save your life,
that means we're friends forever.

378
00:20:33,041 --> 00:20:35,121
(LAUGHS) Yeah, I can deal with that.

379
00:20:35,921 --> 00:20:36,921
(SUDDEN NOISE)

380
00:20:39,081 --> 00:20:40,961
-Why is it going dark?
-The sun is setting.

381
00:20:41,401 --> 00:20:45,201
Nah, it's the beast. It's circling us.
It's looking for a way in.

382
00:20:51,601 --> 00:20:54,561
It's getting stronger again.
Strong enough to feed.

383
00:20:55,681 --> 00:20:59,281
Every hour of sunlight that feeds it
makes the world darker,

384
00:21:00,281 --> 00:21:01,841
and the beast stronger.

385
00:21:04,281 --> 00:21:05,681
We've got very little time.

386
00:21:05,761 --> 00:21:09,081
I have to stop it. This is my fault.

387
00:21:09,601 --> 00:21:11,561
I'm the keeper of the gate.
I have to put this right.

388
00:21:11,641 --> 00:21:13,121
THE DOCTOR:
So, you were supposed to guard the gate

389
00:21:13,201 --> 00:21:14,401
while everyone else went off to war.

390
00:21:14,481 --> 00:21:17,241
But, you had strangers at the door
and a guard dog in the attic,

391
00:21:17,321 --> 00:21:19,121
so you let the beast come through.

392
00:21:19,201 --> 00:21:20,801
It was the only thing
that would defeat them.

393
00:21:20,881 --> 00:21:24,241
So you thought the eater of light
could destroy a whole Roman army?

394
00:21:24,321 --> 00:21:25,321
It did.

395
00:21:25,401 --> 00:21:28,681
And a whole Roman army
could weaken or kill the beast?

396
00:21:29,521 --> 00:21:31,361
-Yes.
-Well, it didn't work.

397
00:21:31,761 --> 00:21:33,241
You got a whole
Roman legion slaughtered,

398
00:21:33,321 --> 00:21:36,561
and you made the deadliest creature
on this planet very, very cross indeed.

399
00:21:37,001 --> 00:21:40,961
To protect a muddy little hillside,
you doomed your whole world.

400
00:21:43,681 --> 00:21:46,441
One man?
You think one man can save us all?

401
00:21:46,521 --> 00:21:47,601
Come and meet him.

402
00:21:48,041 --> 00:21:49,641
He came here to meet you.

403
00:21:50,401 --> 00:21:54,121
He's met loads of people like you,
they're terrified, they're desperate.

404
00:21:54,201 --> 00:21:56,801
And he always helps.
He always makes a difference.

405
00:21:56,881 --> 00:21:58,681
LUCIUS: There are
painted barbarians out there.

406
00:21:59,321 --> 00:22:00,961
They outnumber us.

407
00:22:01,241 --> 00:22:03,521
There is a beast of darkness
that laid waste

408
00:22:03,601 --> 00:22:05,601
to an entire legion
in less than an hour.

409
00:22:05,681 --> 00:22:07,521
No one man
can make a difference to that.

410
00:22:07,601 --> 00:22:09,041
Maybe that's what you don't learn

411
00:22:09,121 --> 00:22:12,161
when you think it takes
5,000 highly trained soldiers

412
00:22:12,241 --> 00:22:14,201
to slaughter
a bunch of Scottish farmers.

413
00:22:14,601 --> 00:22:16,721
Yes, one man can.

414
00:22:17,001 --> 00:22:18,401
And he's here.

415
00:22:18,481 --> 00:22:22,761
If you're calling us cowards, carry on.
We already ran away. We know.

416
00:22:23,201 --> 00:22:24,241
You're not cowards.

417
00:22:25,641 --> 00:22:26,641
You're scared.

418
00:22:28,321 --> 00:22:29,321
Scared is fine.

419
00:22:29,481 --> 00:22:30,721
Scared is human.

420
00:22:31,681 --> 00:22:34,841
I'll tell you what it isn't.
It isn't a plan.

421
00:22:37,281 --> 00:22:38,281
She's right.

422
00:22:38,361 --> 00:22:39,841
Why are you even
listening to her, Grandad?

423
00:22:39,921 --> 00:22:42,241
Because no-one else is saying anything.

424
00:22:44,921 --> 00:22:45,921
We need a plan.

425
00:22:46,441 --> 00:22:48,161
A real commander would have a plan.

426
00:22:55,761 --> 00:22:57,281
Why do they call you Grandad?

427
00:22:58,401 --> 00:22:59,921
They always call me Grandad.

428
00:23:01,041 --> 00:23:03,841
I'm the commander.
I'm the oldest one left.

429
00:23:05,761 --> 00:23:06,761
How old are you?

430
00:23:08,361 --> 00:23:09,361
Eighteen.

431
00:23:12,921 --> 00:23:15,081
Right, listen to me. All of you.

432
00:23:16,881 --> 00:23:18,481
I'm going up there to find my friend.

433
00:23:18,761 --> 00:23:20,081
And if you come with me...

434
00:23:21,641 --> 00:23:23,561
I can't promise that you won't all die.

435
00:23:24,641 --> 00:23:26,081
But I can promise you this.

436
00:23:26,801 --> 00:23:28,881
You won't all die
in a hole in the ground.

437
00:23:35,361 --> 00:23:36,801
THE DOCTOR:
We have to drive it back through

438
00:23:36,881 --> 00:23:39,121
and close the portal behind it.

439
00:23:39,201 --> 00:23:42,481
Now the gate only opens
when the dawn sun hits it. Why is that?

440
00:23:45,401 --> 00:23:48,001
Our ancestors couldn't
close the gate completely.

441
00:23:48,401 --> 00:23:50,201
But they built the cairn to control it.

442
00:23:50,281 --> 00:23:53,081
Ah, like venting an oil gush?

443
00:23:53,161 --> 00:23:55,761
If they let the portal open
a few moments every year,

444
00:23:55,841 --> 00:23:57,561
they stop the whole thing ripping apart.

445
00:23:57,961 --> 00:23:59,361
Yeah, it's quite clever, really.

446
00:24:00,481 --> 00:24:01,481
Are you sulking?

447
00:24:02,561 --> 00:24:03,881
I'm remembering the dead.

448
00:24:04,121 --> 00:24:06,641
Ah, all right.
Well, save that for old age.

449
00:24:07,201 --> 00:24:08,401
They're dead because of me.

450
00:24:08,481 --> 00:24:11,321
You know, every moment you waste
wallowing about in that happy thought,

451
00:24:11,401 --> 00:24:13,161
means more of the living
are going to join them.

452
00:24:14,201 --> 00:24:16,401
When you want to win a war,
remember this.

453
00:24:17,001 --> 00:24:18,001
It's not about you.

454
00:24:18,841 --> 00:24:19,841
Believe me, I know.

455
00:24:20,761 --> 00:24:21,761
Time to grow up.

456
00:24:24,641 --> 00:24:25,641
Time to fight your fight.

457
00:24:27,921 --> 00:24:28,921
How does this work?

458
00:24:29,881 --> 00:24:31,961
It poisons the light
as the beast eats it.

459
00:24:32,041 --> 00:24:33,081
Good.

460
00:24:34,641 --> 00:24:35,641
We'll need more of this.

461
00:24:36,281 --> 00:24:38,401
It has optical cancellation properties.

462
00:24:39,841 --> 00:24:41,881
Now, we have one chance.

463
00:24:42,521 --> 00:24:45,041
Right now, it's weak,
it's injured, it's starving.

464
00:24:45,121 --> 00:24:48,241
But when the sun comes up,
it will feed and grow strong.

465
00:24:48,321 --> 00:24:49,921
We have to lure it back
through the portal

466
00:24:50,001 --> 00:24:51,761
before that happens, before sunrise.

467
00:24:51,841 --> 00:24:53,121
Now, I've got a plan.

468
00:24:54,521 --> 00:24:55,721
But I need your help.

469
00:24:56,601 --> 00:24:57,601
But I'm afraid.

470
00:24:58,161 --> 00:24:59,161
Who isn't?

471
00:25:00,121 --> 00:25:02,441
But you've still got to
face your beast, anyway.

472
00:25:05,641 --> 00:25:06,641
Can you do that?

473
00:25:09,081 --> 00:25:10,081
Aye.

474
00:25:27,361 --> 00:25:29,241
-(WHOOSHING)
-Shh!

475
00:25:31,401 --> 00:25:32,641
LUCIUS: (WHISPERING) It's nothing.

476
00:25:33,321 --> 00:25:35,121
It's the wind in the rocks.

477
00:25:36,081 --> 00:25:38,441
Forward, centurion. Keep going.

478
00:25:39,881 --> 00:25:42,521
There are lots of entrances
the beast could get through.

479
00:25:42,881 --> 00:25:44,001
It's a labyrinth.

480
00:25:47,001 --> 00:25:48,201
(WIND HOWLING)

481
00:25:53,681 --> 00:25:55,081
This is where we hear them.

482
00:25:55,361 --> 00:25:58,481
Barbarians. Right up there.

483
00:25:58,561 --> 00:25:59,641
Up above us.

484
00:25:59,721 --> 00:26:01,281
Are you sure
your friend will be with them?

485
00:26:01,361 --> 00:26:02,441
Yeah.

486
00:26:02,961 --> 00:26:05,481
Basically, he always ends up
being boss of the locals.

487
00:26:05,561 --> 00:26:07,721
-How?
-Usually by knowing them.

488
00:26:09,481 --> 00:26:10,521
(GROWLING)

489
00:26:11,321 --> 00:26:12,321
What was that?

490
00:26:14,161 --> 00:26:16,721
LUCIUS: All right, centurions.
Stay sharp.

491
00:26:16,801 --> 00:26:19,441
-That's the way out, so let's get out.
-Easy, Cornelius.

492
00:26:19,521 --> 00:26:21,361
Let's make sure we know
what we're walking into.

493
00:26:21,441 --> 00:26:23,081
No, let's go.

494
00:26:23,921 --> 00:26:25,041
(PANICKED ARGUING)

495
00:26:25,161 --> 00:26:26,441
(ROARING)

496
00:26:28,561 --> 00:26:29,681
(SCREAMS)

497
00:26:36,361 --> 00:26:37,441
(ALL SCREAM)

498
00:26:37,521 --> 00:26:38,681
Come quickly!

499
00:26:39,361 --> 00:26:40,721
Douse the fire, quickly!

500
00:26:41,081 --> 00:26:42,081
(FIRE HISSES OUT)

501
00:26:44,641 --> 00:26:45,961
Shift your arse, Roman!

502
00:26:54,601 --> 00:26:55,841
Close the trap door.

503
00:26:58,401 --> 00:27:00,321
Block it off. We have to block it off.

504
00:27:00,841 --> 00:27:02,921
Centurions! Defence formation.

505
00:27:04,081 --> 00:27:06,361
It's fallen back. It's waiting.

506
00:27:06,681 --> 00:27:09,921
It's waiting to feed off the sunlight,
to grow to its full strength.

507
00:27:10,001 --> 00:27:11,361
-Hello.
-Hi.

508
00:27:13,241 --> 00:27:14,401
I brought you the Ninth Legion.

509
00:27:14,761 --> 00:27:16,081
THE DOCTOR: Oh, there they are.

510
00:27:16,201 --> 00:27:18,281
The lost legion of the Ninth.

511
00:27:18,761 --> 00:27:19,761
Totally found them.

512
00:27:19,841 --> 00:27:21,081
Yeah, you totally did.

513
00:27:22,881 --> 00:27:23,881
BILL: Nardole!

514
00:27:26,081 --> 00:27:28,801
-What happened to you?
-Oh, I'm blending in.

515
00:27:28,881 --> 00:27:31,601
(SCOTTISH ACCENT) Hmm.
Welcome to our land.

516
00:27:31,681 --> 00:27:33,041
(CHUCKLES) Scotch.

517
00:27:33,121 --> 00:27:34,441
Drop your weapons.

518
00:27:34,521 --> 00:27:36,201
Oh, for goodness sake,
we don't have time for this!

519
00:27:36,281 --> 00:27:37,921
-Stay back!
-Lucius, stop it!

520
00:27:38,001 --> 00:27:39,321
Are you their champion now?

521
00:27:39,401 --> 00:27:42,921
-There is no time for fighting.
-Exactly.

522
00:27:43,001 --> 00:27:44,561
We never wanted to fight!

523
00:27:45,521 --> 00:27:48,161
We lived in peace and then you came.

524
00:27:48,681 --> 00:27:51,561
And laid waste to everything
and everyone we loved.

525
00:27:51,641 --> 00:27:53,801
All you understand is war.

526
00:27:53,881 --> 00:27:55,281
No, he understands.

527
00:27:56,201 --> 00:27:57,201
Don't you?

528
00:27:57,801 --> 00:27:59,521
Now he's wondering why.

529
00:28:00,921 --> 00:28:02,241
You speak Latin?

530
00:28:02,441 --> 00:28:03,441
I don't.

531
00:28:05,041 --> 00:28:07,161
Neither do I. Not a word.

532
00:28:08,241 --> 00:28:10,681
BILL: And I don't speak
whatever they speak either.

533
00:28:10,801 --> 00:28:11,801
It's him.

534
00:28:13,441 --> 00:28:14,441
It's you, isn't it?

535
00:28:14,761 --> 00:28:15,761
Yes, it's me.

536
00:28:16,161 --> 00:28:18,561
Something to do with the TARDIS, maybe?
Telepathic field?

537
00:28:19,041 --> 00:28:22,081
So now that we all understand
each other, how do we all sound?

538
00:28:23,001 --> 00:28:24,201
You sound like children.

539
00:28:24,521 --> 00:28:27,121
-You sound like children, too.
-You all do.

540
00:28:27,281 --> 00:28:28,281
BILL: This is what happens.

541
00:28:28,441 --> 00:28:31,281
You can understand what everyone
in the universe is saying.

542
00:28:31,681 --> 00:28:33,361
Everybody just sounds like children.

543
00:28:33,641 --> 00:28:34,841
There are exceptions.

544
00:28:35,521 --> 00:28:37,201
-Thank you very much.
-THE DOCTOR: Not you.

545
00:28:37,961 --> 00:28:41,481
Okay, kids, pay attention.

546
00:28:42,321 --> 00:28:43,401
She slaughtered your legion,

547
00:28:43,481 --> 00:28:45,921
you slaughtered
everything that she loves.

548
00:28:46,001 --> 00:28:47,841
Now, you all have a choice,

549
00:28:47,921 --> 00:28:50,561
you can carry on
slaughtering each other,

550
00:28:51,121 --> 00:28:52,961
till no one is left standing,

551
00:28:53,041 --> 00:28:54,601
or you grow the hell up!

552
00:28:55,161 --> 00:28:56,521
Because there's a new war now.

553
00:28:57,481 --> 00:29:03,481
I think these creatures
are light-eating locusts,

554
00:29:04,681 --> 00:29:06,681
looking for rents and cracks

555
00:29:06,761 --> 00:29:10,041
between worlds to let themselves
into dimensions of light.

556
00:29:11,681 --> 00:29:13,121
Once they break through,

557
00:29:13,881 --> 00:29:14,881
they eat.

558
00:29:16,761 --> 00:29:18,161
They will eat the sun.

559
00:29:19,481 --> 00:29:23,081
And then, they will eat the stars.

560
00:29:24,641 --> 00:29:27,201
And they will keep eating until...

561
00:29:29,761 --> 00:29:31,601
There are no stars left.

562
00:29:34,681 --> 00:29:36,041
So, whose side are you on, now?

563
00:29:36,121 --> 00:29:38,921
Because as far as I can see,
there is only one side left.

564
00:29:43,201 --> 00:29:44,801
If it helps,

565
00:29:46,241 --> 00:29:47,721
I do have a plan.

566
00:29:57,361 --> 00:30:00,601
THE DOCTOR: It feeds on light,
but it homes in on sound.

567
00:30:00,921 --> 00:30:02,001
BILL: So, what's going to happen?

568
00:30:02,081 --> 00:30:04,401
It's simple. Bit of noise,

569
00:30:04,481 --> 00:30:08,241
lure the beast here,
drive it back through the gate.

570
00:30:08,601 --> 00:30:10,281
But how do we keep it there?

571
00:30:10,921 --> 00:30:13,081
I mean, you said all those things
are going to come through, right?

572
00:30:13,161 --> 00:30:14,881
Well, they can only come through
one at a time.

573
00:30:14,961 --> 00:30:17,241
-I know.
-That's why guarding the gate worked.

574
00:30:17,321 --> 00:30:19,681
One Pict in there,
fighting it off for a few minutes.

575
00:30:19,761 --> 00:30:22,081
That adds up to 60 or 70 years out here.

576
00:30:22,401 --> 00:30:24,801
I get it, yeah,
and then the next one goes in.

577
00:30:25,601 --> 00:30:27,041
But what are we going to do this time?

578
00:30:27,361 --> 00:30:28,481
Or are you going to line up Picts

579
00:30:28,561 --> 00:30:31,001
sacrificing themselves
until the end of the world?

580
00:30:32,241 --> 00:30:33,801
I've got a better idea this time.

581
00:30:34,361 --> 00:30:36,161
Which is the part you never tell me!

582
00:30:36,601 --> 00:30:37,801
-Don't I?
-Uh-uh.

583
00:30:37,921 --> 00:30:39,481
I'll probably just get interrupted.

584
00:30:39,561 --> 00:30:41,881
(LAUGHING AND BAGPIPE MUSIC)

585
00:30:47,361 --> 00:30:49,041
This is worse than jazz.

586
00:30:51,921 --> 00:30:54,041
-Nothing. There's nothing.
-Hmm.

587
00:30:55,481 --> 00:30:56,521
Maybe it won't come.

588
00:30:57,641 --> 00:30:58,681
-Hello.
-(CAWS)

589
00:30:59,001 --> 00:31:00,001
CROW: (CAWING) Hello.

590
00:31:00,361 --> 00:31:01,361
Hello.

591
00:31:01,601 --> 00:31:03,001
CROW: (CAWING) Doctor.

592
00:31:03,201 --> 00:31:05,121
No, no, Nardole.

593
00:31:06,161 --> 00:31:08,521
Yeah, it's probably a bit tricky
for you, that, innit?

594
00:31:08,801 --> 00:31:09,801
(CAWS)

595
00:31:10,321 --> 00:31:12,601
Huh! Lovely! (CHUCKLES) Hello.

596
00:31:12,681 --> 00:31:14,721
-CROW: (CAWING) Monster!
-Sorry?

597
00:31:15,441 --> 00:31:16,521
(CAWS) Monster!

598
00:31:16,961 --> 00:31:18,121
(SNARLING)

599
00:31:18,761 --> 00:31:19,801
There!

600
00:31:22,161 --> 00:31:23,161
(ROARING)

601
00:31:23,681 --> 00:31:24,841
Oh!

602
00:31:25,721 --> 00:31:27,241
-It's coming.
-It's here.

603
00:31:27,321 --> 00:31:28,321
Get ready!

604
00:31:29,681 --> 00:31:30,801
Turn on the light!

605
00:31:32,161 --> 00:31:33,161
(ROARING)

606
00:31:36,281 --> 00:31:37,281
THE DOCTOR: Keep it here.

607
00:31:38,281 --> 00:31:40,201
We've got to hold it here till sunrise.

608
00:31:41,681 --> 00:31:42,681
Ah!

609
00:31:46,961 --> 00:31:48,001
Keep it there!

610
00:31:48,841 --> 00:31:49,881
Keep it there!

611
00:31:55,361 --> 00:31:56,481
(GRUNTING)

612
00:31:57,921 --> 00:31:59,681
THE DOCTOR: Turn her! The sun is rising!

613
00:32:07,041 --> 00:32:08,881
Back! Back to the void!

614
00:32:25,841 --> 00:32:28,041
It'll only stay open as long as
the sunlight's on it.

615
00:32:29,121 --> 00:32:30,361
Give me your weapon.

616
00:32:30,441 --> 00:32:31,441
What are you doing?

617
00:32:31,521 --> 00:32:33,241
-THE DOCTOR: This is the clever bit.
-Well, tell me.

618
00:32:33,321 --> 00:32:35,001
The gate has to be guarded.
There's no other way.

619
00:32:35,121 --> 00:32:36,921
The trouble is, human lifespans.

620
00:32:37,321 --> 00:32:38,641
They're tiny.

621
00:32:38,761 --> 00:32:41,121
They're hilarious.
You get used up too quickly.

622
00:32:41,641 --> 00:32:44,001
So what's the answer?
Go on, figure it out.

623
00:32:45,961 --> 00:32:51,081
The answer is me. I go on for ages.
I don't even really die, I regenerate.

624
00:32:51,481 --> 00:32:54,441
I can hold that gate
until the sun goes out.

625
00:32:54,521 --> 00:32:57,561
-No, you can't.
-Of course, I can. I'm going to.

626
00:32:58,161 --> 00:32:59,601
This isn't your job.

627
00:32:59,681 --> 00:33:01,401
No it isn't, Bill. It's who I am.

628
00:33:01,761 --> 00:33:03,841
I've been standing
by the gates of your world,

629
00:33:04,401 --> 00:33:07,321
keeping you all safe
since you crawled out of the slime.

630
00:33:07,401 --> 00:33:09,801
-I'm not stopping now.
-Doctor, please!

631
00:33:09,881 --> 00:33:11,841
Listen, the TARDIS will take you home.

632
00:33:11,921 --> 00:33:13,721
-Return journeys are easy.
-Listen to me.

633
00:33:13,801 --> 00:33:15,601
Leave the instruments
on the current setting.

634
00:33:15,681 --> 00:33:17,321
Just hit them with a spanner.

635
00:33:17,561 --> 00:33:18,681
Weapon, now.

636
00:33:18,761 --> 00:33:20,841
-No.
-Give it to me, come on.

637
00:33:20,921 --> 00:33:22,881
You'll be safe.
Tomorrow, you'll be farming.

638
00:33:22,961 --> 00:33:24,441
And you can name a cow after me.

639
00:33:24,521 --> 00:33:26,161
What about the other gates
that you have to guard?

640
00:33:26,241 --> 00:33:27,481
What about the vault?

641
00:33:27,561 --> 00:33:29,881
The vault will never exist
if I let those things come through!

642
00:33:29,961 --> 00:33:31,081
Well, then somebody else
better stop them!

643
00:33:31,161 --> 00:33:32,961
-Nobody else can.
-I can!

644
00:33:33,641 --> 00:33:34,761
What did you say?

645
00:33:34,841 --> 00:33:38,201
Time to grow up, Doctor.
Time to fight my fight.

646
00:33:38,281 --> 00:33:39,281
(ROARS)

647
00:33:41,241 --> 00:33:44,081
I'm sorry, no. No one else can do this.
Not like I can.

648
00:33:44,281 --> 00:33:46,321
We can. I'm ready.

649
00:33:46,401 --> 00:33:49,441
I'll guard the gate with you.
I'll fight by your side.

650
00:33:49,721 --> 00:33:52,481
Awesome. Brilliant.
You'll be a hero for two seconds.

651
00:33:52,561 --> 00:33:54,961
Then the whole solar system
will be devoured.

652
00:33:56,561 --> 00:33:57,561
Stop him!

653
00:33:58,041 --> 00:34:00,441
This is my destiny, my fight!

654
00:34:00,641 --> 00:34:02,121
Out of my way! Now!

655
00:34:02,481 --> 00:34:04,681
-We'll take it in turns.
-The two of you can't hold the gate.

656
00:34:04,761 --> 00:34:06,961
Two of them? I'm counting more than two.

657
00:34:07,241 --> 00:34:09,361
The Legion of the Ninth
stands ready to serve.

658
00:34:09,481 --> 00:34:12,201
Oh, stop being brave.
I can't bear brave people.

659
00:34:12,561 --> 00:34:15,681
I'll put the story in the stone.
I'll put your name in the air.

660
00:34:16,201 --> 00:34:19,361
They'll see it for hundreds of years
and they'll know your name forever.

661
00:34:19,441 --> 00:34:20,441
Good!

662
00:34:24,361 --> 00:34:25,361
Ready?

663
00:34:25,441 --> 00:34:27,601
No, listen to me. No! Listen...

664
00:34:28,681 --> 00:34:29,761
BILL: You're wrong, Doctor.

665
00:34:29,961 --> 00:34:31,161
It's their destiny.

666
00:34:32,481 --> 00:34:33,521
Not yours.

667
00:34:35,721 --> 00:34:37,041
NARDOLE: Sorry, you're going nowhere.

668
00:34:37,601 --> 00:34:40,241
-THE DOCTOR: Bill! Bill, stop it!
-Quickly. Quickly.

669
00:34:40,321 --> 00:34:42,961
Soldiers of the Ninth! Advance!

670
00:34:43,241 --> 00:34:44,401
Come on!

671
00:34:44,641 --> 00:34:45,641
(SHOUTING)

672
00:34:46,161 --> 00:34:47,361
(BAGPIPES PLAYING)

673
00:35:15,201 --> 00:35:16,201
(LOUD CRASHING)

674
00:35:16,761 --> 00:35:17,761
What's that?

675
00:35:18,681 --> 00:35:19,761
What's happening?

676
00:35:20,121 --> 00:35:21,921
Too many of them going through at once.

677
00:35:22,281 --> 00:35:23,601
This place is unstable.

678
00:35:23,881 --> 00:35:25,841
We need to get out of here! Now!

679
00:35:27,921 --> 00:35:29,081
NARDOLE: Oh! Oh!

680
00:35:29,361 --> 00:35:30,361
(BOTH PANTING)

681
00:35:34,841 --> 00:35:35,841
(CAWING)

682
00:35:40,081 --> 00:35:41,521
NARDOLE: I know you're inclined
to bear a grudge,

683
00:35:41,601 --> 00:35:45,281
so just remember, I know
about 10% of your secrets,

684
00:35:45,441 --> 00:35:46,681
the dark secrets,

685
00:35:47,081 --> 00:35:51,041
and, I'm the only one in the TARDIS
who knows where the teacakes are.

686
00:35:57,081 --> 00:35:58,481
-(CRIES) Kar.
-CROW: (CAWING) Kart!

687
00:35:59,121 --> 00:36:00,601
She's holding the gate.

688
00:36:01,561 --> 00:36:03,121
Remember, her name is Kar.

689
00:36:03,561 --> 00:36:05,401
-CROW: (CAWING) Kar! Kar!
-Kar.

690
00:36:06,961 --> 00:36:07,961
(CAWS)

691
00:36:11,121 --> 00:36:12,401
You were wrong.

692
00:36:13,081 --> 00:36:14,481
The crows aren't sulking.

693
00:36:16,201 --> 00:36:20,041
-The crows are remembering.
-(CROW CAWS)

694
00:36:23,721 --> 00:36:26,881
BILL: I'm sorry, Doctor,
but you have a vault to guard.

695
00:36:27,241 --> 00:36:29,081
You can't take on every fight.

696
00:36:32,241 --> 00:36:33,561
All right, I was wrong.

697
00:36:34,961 --> 00:36:37,241
I didn't know what really happened
to the Ninth Legion.

698
00:36:37,321 --> 00:36:39,041
No, we were both wrong about that.

699
00:36:40,241 --> 00:36:42,001
They were never really missing.

700
00:36:42,961 --> 00:36:44,041
They've always been here.

701
00:36:45,481 --> 00:36:47,041
The Ninth Legion
and the keeper of the gate.

702
00:36:48,521 --> 00:36:50,401
Seizing the day till the sun goes out.

703
00:36:51,441 --> 00:36:52,961
Holding back the dark.

704
00:36:53,241 --> 00:36:54,801
(BAGPIPES PLAYING FAINTLY)

705
00:36:58,481 --> 00:36:59,481
What?

706
00:37:00,681 --> 00:37:03,121
I thought... Did you hear that?

707
00:37:06,041 --> 00:37:07,321
I thought I could hear the music,

708
00:37:07,401 --> 00:37:10,121
but I can't, can I?
They're in another time.

709
00:37:11,561 --> 00:37:13,001
Music's funny like that.

710
00:37:23,521 --> 00:37:24,561
(CAWS)

711
00:37:29,241 --> 00:37:30,321
Right.

712
00:37:31,201 --> 00:37:32,761
Shall we go back home?

713
00:37:32,841 --> 00:37:36,161
Time you were guarding that vault,
we don't want Missy getting any ideas.

714
00:37:36,241 --> 00:37:38,121
MISSY: One should always
try to avoid those.

715
00:37:39,601 --> 00:37:43,841
Hello! Well, you lot were ages,
I was getting ever so worried.

716
00:37:44,001 --> 00:37:45,681
How did you get out of the vault?

717
00:37:46,081 --> 00:37:47,561
Sir, what do we do?
How could this happen?

718
00:37:47,641 --> 00:37:49,601
It's all right, Nardole,
she's been doing some work for me.

719
00:37:49,681 --> 00:37:53,161
Sorry, I'm sorry, I'm so sorry,
I assumed they knew.

720
00:37:53,401 --> 00:37:55,201
Should I have stayed below decks?

721
00:37:55,401 --> 00:37:56,841
No. no, no, no, it's fine.

722
00:37:56,921 --> 00:37:58,761
She's supposed to be in the vault!

723
00:37:59,801 --> 00:38:00,961
How are the engines?

724
00:38:01,041 --> 00:38:03,161
Better than you deserve.
You are naughty.

725
00:38:03,241 --> 00:38:04,801
Do you ever do basic maintenance?

726
00:38:04,881 --> 00:38:06,281
THE DOCTOR: No,
but I've got a plan for that.

727
00:38:06,361 --> 00:38:07,961
-What?
-You.

728
00:38:08,041 --> 00:38:10,961
What, seriously? What, what
she's doing chores for you now?

729
00:38:11,041 --> 00:38:15,721
Sir, I must protest in the strongest,
most upset terms possible.

730
00:38:15,801 --> 00:38:18,121
Don't make me go squeaky-voiced.

731
00:38:18,241 --> 00:38:20,201
Do relax, you two.

732
00:38:20,281 --> 00:38:21,881
I'm bio-locked out of the controls,

733
00:38:21,961 --> 00:38:23,761
I can't even get through those doors.

734
00:38:23,881 --> 00:38:26,401
I'm as much a prisoner here
as I am in the vault.

735
00:38:26,481 --> 00:38:28,401
No, you most certainly are not.

736
00:38:28,641 --> 00:38:31,841
Doctor, seriously.
Why did you let her out?

737
00:38:32,241 --> 00:38:34,641
THE DOCTOR: I think you may be
forgetting how we got home from Mars.

738
00:38:36,001 --> 00:38:37,001
What, so now you trust her?

739
00:38:37,081 --> 00:38:40,001
No, so now he's getting
TARDIS maintenance for free.

740
00:38:40,641 --> 00:38:42,841
Let's not get carried away.

741
00:38:42,921 --> 00:38:44,721
THE DOCTOR: So what have you been up to?

742
00:38:44,801 --> 00:38:45,801
Did you watch us?

743
00:38:45,881 --> 00:38:47,601
-Some of it. A little bit.
-THE DOCTOR: What did you think?

744
00:38:47,681 --> 00:38:50,841
-Oh, is she reviewing us now?
-MISSY: Oh, those little people.

745
00:38:50,921 --> 00:38:53,041
Trapped in a hill fighting forever.

746
00:38:53,841 --> 00:38:56,161
Is that really up to
your bleeding heart standards?

747
00:38:56,441 --> 00:38:59,361
Well, they're not trapped.
And they're more than just fighting.

748
00:38:59,441 --> 00:39:00,841
And there's music.

749
00:39:01,561 --> 00:39:02,721
Always music.

750
00:39:03,481 --> 00:39:07,281
Well, team.
Who's going to help me hide his guitar?

751
00:39:07,721 --> 00:39:09,241
See, that's what I'm trying
to teach you, Missy.

752
00:39:09,401 --> 00:39:12,361
You understand the universe.
You see it, you grasp it.

753
00:39:12,921 --> 00:39:14,881
But you never learn to hear the music.

754
00:39:24,121 --> 00:39:25,641
(BAGPIPES PLAYING FAINTLY)

755
00:39:41,441 --> 00:39:42,441
(CHUCKLES)

756
00:40:02,681 --> 00:40:03,681
Huh.

757
00:40:06,961 --> 00:40:10,401
I don't even know why I'm crying.
Why do I keep doing that now?

758
00:40:10,601 --> 00:40:11,601
I don't know.

759
00:40:12,881 --> 00:40:14,521
Maybe you're trying to impress me.

760
00:40:17,041 --> 00:40:18,041
Yes.

761
00:40:18,841 --> 00:40:21,681
Probably some devious plan.
That sounds about right.

762
00:40:24,601 --> 00:40:26,601
Well, the alternative
would be much worse.

763
00:40:28,121 --> 00:40:29,121
Really?

764
00:40:33,281 --> 00:40:35,681
The alternative
is that this is for real.

765
00:40:37,001 --> 00:40:40,321
And it's time for us
to become friends again.

766
00:40:42,601 --> 00:40:43,601
Do you think so?

767
00:40:52,521 --> 00:40:53,521
I don't know.

768
00:40:54,561 --> 00:40:56,121
That's the trouble with hope.

769
00:40:59,601 --> 00:41:00,841
It's hard to resist.

770
00:41:18,561 --> 00:41:19,601
THE DOCTOR: I pick a scenario.

771
00:41:19,681 --> 00:41:21,281
We drop her down into it
and we see how she does.

772
00:41:21,361 --> 00:41:22,361
Hello.

773
00:41:22,441 --> 00:41:26,961
I am that mysterious adventurer
in all of time and space.

774
00:41:27,041 --> 00:41:28,881
And these are my disposables.

775
00:41:28,961 --> 00:41:30,481
Just promise you won't get me killed.

776
00:41:30,721 --> 00:41:32,041
I said this was a bad idea.

777
00:41:32,761 --> 00:41:33,961
THE DOCTOR: A 400-mile ship

778
00:41:34,041 --> 00:41:38,241
reversing away from
the gravitational pull of a black hole.

779
00:41:39,401 --> 00:41:41,081
I'm so sorry, but you're the reason
that they're coming.

780
00:41:43,881 --> 00:41:44,881
NARDOLE: What are they?

781
00:41:45,001 --> 00:41:47,201
A Mondasian Cyberman.

782
00:41:47,921 --> 00:41:49,081
Give us a kiss.

783
00:41:49,681 --> 00:41:51,681
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

